            "creation_date": 1527402306,
            "body": "<p>I think that happened because your filter and sink have been assigned to another TStream object, not the one you are printing out.<br>\nProbably you need to try this:  <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>TempSensor ts = new TempSensor();\nTStream&lt;Double&gt; temp = top.poll(ts, 1, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS).filter(tuple -&gt;\ntuple &lt; OPTIMAL_TEMP_LOW || tuple &gt; OPTIMAL_TEMP_HIGH);\ntemp.sink(tuple -&gt; System.out.println(\"Temperature is out of range! \"\n+ \"It is \" + tuple + \"\\u00b0F!\"));\n\n// See what the temperatures look like\ntemp.print();\n\ndp.submit(top);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 50549580,
            "question_id": 50549019,
            "last_edit_date": 1527403763
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/Otxpb.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 34940,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 98806,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/98806/richard-inglis",
                "reputation": 5968,
                "display_name": "Richard Inglis",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1527412480,
            "creation_date": 1527412480,
            "body": "<p>Hmm, your code matches the example in the documentation, but it looks as if we\u2019re creating a filtered stream, and then ignoring it in <code>temp.print()<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>You could try changing that line to <code>simpleFiltered.print()<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 50550678,
            "question_id": 50549019
        }
    ],
